	<div id="content">
		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Wardenclyffe Tower</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For the Allan Holdsworth album, see <a href="/wiki/Wardenclyffe_Tower_(album)" title="Wardenclyffe Tower (album)">Wardenclyffe Tower (album)</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:335px;"><a href="/wiki/File:BrochureWardenclyffe_.PNG" class="image" title="Wardenclyffe Tower located in Shoreham, Long Island, New York. The 94&#160;ft (29&#160;m) by 94&#160;ft (29&#160;m) brick building was designed by architect Stanford White. The station, including the tower structure was not completed due to financial difficulties."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/ff/BrochureWardenclyffe_.PNG/333px-BrochureWardenclyffe_.PNG" width="333" height="211" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:BrochureWardenclyffe_.PNG" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Wardenclyffe Tower located in <a href="/wiki/Shoreham,_New_York" title="Shoreham, New York">Shoreham</a>, <a href="/wiki/Long_Island" title="Long Island">Long Island</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_York" title="New York">New York</a>. The 94&#160;ft (29&#160;m) by 94&#160;ft (29&#160;m) brick building was designed by architect <a href="/wiki/Stanford_White" title="Stanford White">Stanford White</a>. The station, including the tower structure was not completed due to financial difficulties.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Wardenclyffe Tower</b> (1901–1917) also known as the <b>Tesla Tower</b>, was an early <a href="/wiki/Wireless" title="Wireless">wireless</a> <a href="/wiki/Telecommunications" title="Telecommunications" class="mw-redirect">telecommunications</a> tower designed by <a href="/wiki/Nikola_Tesla" title="Nikola Tesla">Nikola Tesla</a> and intended for commercial <a href="/wiki/Trans-Atlantic" title="Trans-Atlantic" class="mw-redirect">trans-Atlantic</a> <a href="/wiki/Wireless" title="Wireless">wireless</a> <a href="/wiki/Telephony" title="Telephony">telephony</a>, broadcasting, and to demonstrate the <a href="/wiki/Wireless_energy_transfer" title="Wireless energy transfer">transmission of power without interconnecting wires</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> The core facility was never fully operational and was not completed due to economic problems.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The tower was named after James S. Warden, a western <a href="/wiki/Lawyer" title="Lawyer">lawyer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Banker" title="Banker" class="mw-redirect">banker</a> who had purchased land in <a href="/wiki/Shoreham,_New_York" title="Shoreham, New York">Shoreham</a>, <a href="/wiki/Long_Island" title="Long Island">Long Island</a>, about sixty miles from <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a>. Here he built a resort community known as Wardenclyffe-On-Sound. Warden believed that with the implementation of Tesla's "world system", a "Radio City" would arise in the area, and he offered Tesla 200 <a href="/wiki/Acre" title="Acre">acres</a> (81 <a href="/wiki/Hectare" title="Hectare">hectares</a>) of land close to a railway line on which to build his wireless telecommunications tower and laboratory facility.</p>
